iplines as diverse as philosophy, sociology, the information sciences and linguistics, “relevance” has been proposed as a key concept. This book is the first to bring together the often unrelated traditions. Researchers from different fields discuss relevance and relate it to the challenges of “irrelevance”, which have so far been neglected despite their significance for our chances of making well-informed decisions and understanding others. The contributions focus on theoretical and conceptual questions, on specific factors and fields, and on practical and political implications of relevance and irrelevance as forces which are even stronger when they remain in the background.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPragmatics. 0aRelevance. 4aKognitionswissenschaft. 4aKommunikation. 4aPhänomenologie. 4aRelevanztheorie. 4aSozialtheorie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aCognitive Science.  aCommunication.  aPhenomenology.  aRelevance Theory.  aSocial Theory.1 aBarber, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButnaru, Denisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorta, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIkeya, Nozomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, Brian N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCrudden, Matthew T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNasu, Hisashi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRapp, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSantos, Hermílio, econtributor.4ctb4https: